TY  - JOUR
AU  - Liu, Claire
AU  - Low, Angie
AU  - Masulis, Ronald W
AU  - Zhang, Le
T1  - Monitoring the Monitor: Distracted Institutional Investors and Board Governance
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa014
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 33
IS  - 10
SP  - 4489
EP  - 4531
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Boards are crucial to shareholder wealth. Yet little is known about how shareholder oversight affects director incentives. Using exogenous shocks to institutional investor portfolios, we find that institutional investor distraction weakens board oversight. Distracted institutions are less likely to discipline ineffective directors with negative votes. Consequently, independent directors face weaker monitoring incentives and exhibit poor board performance; ineffective independent directors are also more frequently appointed. Moreover, we find that the adverse effects of investor distraction on various corporate governance outcomes are stronger among firms with problematic directors. Our findings suggest that institutional investor monitoring creates important director incentives to monitor.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa014
ER  - 



